            , <rs id="t18291203-196-viclabel1013" type="occupation">widow</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291203-196-victim1226 t18291203-196-viclabel1013"></join>.</p>
               <p>CATHERINE LURCHEN. I am a widow. The prisoner is my grandson; he has lived with me some years - I found a number of duplicates one Sunday morning; but I did not miss these articles till I saw them before the Magistrate.</p>
               <p>GEORGE WILLIAMS. I am a pawnbroker. I have a book, pawned by the prisoner, and a tea-kettle, pawned by Richard Avent.</p>
               <p>RICHARD AVENT. I have known the prisoner three months; we used to go to school together - he asked me to pawn this tea-kettle for his grandmother, and I did for 3s.: I gave the prisoner the money - he went in doors with it, then came out and gave me a halfpenny.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291203-196-person1227">
                  FREDERICK 
                  LANCE
               <interp inst="t18291203-196-person1227" type="surname" value="LANCE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291203-196-person1227" type="given" value="FREDERICK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291203-196-person1227" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. I have a shawl, pawned by a person in the name of Smith: I think it was by one of these witnesses.</p>
               <p>RICHARD AVENT. I pawned it for the prisoner; he said his grandmother was ill, and in want of money, and if they asked the name, I was to say Smith.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18291203-196-verdict1014" type="verdictDescription">
